<!-- ✅ 1️⃣ What is Git -->
Git is a distributed version control system used to track changes in source code and manage collaboration between developers.

<!-- 🔥 2️⃣ What is Version Control? -->
Version control is a system that tracks changes to files over time so we can recall specific versions later.

<!-- What is GitHub? -->
GitHub is a cloud-based platform where developers can store and manage Git repositories. It allows teams to collaborate on projects, review code, manage issues, and track changes. 


<!-- 🔥 3️⃣ Difference Between Git and GitHub? -->
Git is a version control system, while GitHub is a cloud platform that hosts Git repositories.


<!-- What is a repository in GitHub -->
A repository is a storage location for a project that contains all project files, code, and version history.

<!-- 🔥 5️⃣ Explain Git Workflow -->
First we initialize the repository using git init, then add files using git add ., commit changes using git commit, and finally push the code to GitHub using git push.

<!-- 🔥 6️⃣ What is a Branch in Git? -->


<!-- 9. Common Git Commands -->
What Git commands do you use?

git init
git add .
git commit -m "message"
git push
git pull
git clone

Explanation:

git init → create new repository
git add → add files to staging area
git commit → save changes
git push → upload code to GitHub
git pull → download latest code 

<!-- 🔥 4️⃣ What is Staging Area? -->
The staging area is a temporary area where changes are prepared before committing.


<!-- What does git clone do -->
Git clone is used to download an existing repository from GitHub to the local system.

git clone https://github.com/projectname

<!-- What is git merge? -->
Git merge combines changes from one branch into another branch, usually merging a feature branch into the main branch.

